WEBVTT

00:01.565 --> 00:04.193
<i>- Gentlemen, if you please.
- We're getting absolutely nowhere.</i>

00:04.318 --> 00:06.695
<i>- May I repeat...
- You made your point, sir.</i>

00:06.820 --> 00:08.948
<i>- For the record, this time.
- For the record,</i>

00:09.073 --> 00:11.450
<i>we are going round and round
and round in circles.</i>

00:11.575 --> 00:13.935
<i>This meeting, I'm beginning to think,
has no shape at all.</i>

00:14.036 --> 00:15.913
<i>No. No shape, nor</i> a <i>purpose. Neither.</i>

00:16.038 --> 00:18.040
May I suggest we start
from the beginning?

00:18.165 --> 00:20.626
No. Let's start at right now.

00:23.295 --> 00:25.548
I want an answer, Mr. Durant.

00:25.881 --> 00:28.259
Not an equivocation,
not a redirect...

00:28.384 --> 00:30.970
A simple answer
to a simple question.

00:31.554 --> 00:35.849
Will the Union Pacific build north or south

00:35.975 --> 00:37.434
of the Great Salt Lake?

00:37.560 --> 00:41.272
The Union Pacific
is planning to build

00:41.397 --> 00:43.190
south to Salt Lake City.

00:43.315 --> 00:46.860
This great city in which we are gathered

00:46.986 --> 00:51.782
is and has always been
our designated terminus.

00:51.907 --> 00:54.201
Are you suggesting
Miss Ellison made this up?

00:54.326 --> 00:58.747
I am stating that Miss Ellison
is a journalist, Mr. President.

00:59.206 --> 01:01.375
She will write anything
to sell newspapers.

01:01.500 --> 01:03.752
I thought her prose well founded,

01:03.877 --> 01:06.547
articulated and... and compelling,
frankly, Mr. Durant.

01:06.672 --> 01:10.092
Nobody is interested
in your literary criticism...

01:10.217 --> 01:12.136
Gentlemen. Per my contract

01:12.261 --> 01:14.638
with Collie Huntington
and the Central Pacific Railroad,

01:14.763 --> 01:17.474
he had agreed to build south
through Salt Lake City.

01:17.600 --> 01:18.934
Cassius?

01:19.476 --> 01:23.480
Yet this map, which I am
recently come to possess,

01:23.606 --> 01:26.358
proves him to be both
a liar and a thief.

01:28.485 --> 01:29.820
Mr. Huntington?

01:32.615 --> 01:35.326
Central Pacific Railroad
intends to build north.

01:35.451 --> 01:40.331
Any, misunderstanding on the part of
Mr. Young is regrettable and unintentional.

01:40.456 --> 01:41.915
I motion

01:42.041 --> 01:45.586
that construction
on the Central Pacific's road

01:45.711 --> 01:48.172
be suspended pending a full inquiry.

01:48.297 --> 01:49.923
I would ask you, Mr. President,

01:50.299 --> 01:52.509
to consider how.

01:52.635 --> 01:54.595
Brigham Young acquired that map,

01:54.720 --> 01:57.056
private property
of the Central Pacific Railroad.

01:57.181 --> 01:58.807
Samuel Ammerman, my...

01:58.932 --> 02:01.226
my telegraph operator,
disappeared ages...

02:01.352 --> 02:05.981
ages ago after being placed there
by Thomas Durant to spy...

02:06.106 --> 02:08.692
That is an unsubstantiated
accusation, sir!

02:08.817 --> 02:10.294
Private business
of a private corporation!

02:10.318 --> 02:11.820
Have not corporations rights, sir?

02:11.945 --> 02:15.366
Now, surely, a penalty
for corporate espionage must be levied.

02:15.491 --> 02:19.662
"Corporate espionage."
You practically invented the concept!

02:19.787 --> 02:20.788
Enough!

02:28.962 --> 02:30.964
- Mr. Bohannon.
- Mr. President.

02:35.344 --> 02:39.682
I promised the American people a railroad
that crosses this country, gentlemen.

02:39.807 --> 02:41.684
It Will be built.

02:41.809 --> 02:44.061
If not by you, by someone else.

02:44.186 --> 02:47.439
We will establish a route
and a terminus,

02:47.564 --> 02:50.109
a place where your two railroads shall meet

02:50.234 --> 02:53.737
before any of us steps foot
outside Salt Lake City.

02:53.862 --> 02:55.239
One hour recess.

